\pard\sa200\sl276\slmult1        OOP is a programming style that organizes code using classes and objects.\par
Encapsulation:\par
 like storing items in a box and control who can accese it protect and secure data\par
Inheritance:\par
allows a class (subclass)to inherit properties and methods from a another class makes it easier to reuse code and create class hierachies.\par
Polymorthism:\par
ability of different objects to respond to same methods in different ways ,methods with same name to have different behaviours depending on type of object .\par
Abstraction process of hiding complex details exposing only what is necessary allows you to use objects without needing to understand all the intricacies on how they work\par
\par
Benefits of OOP:\par
 Code is reusable through inheritance.\par
 Programs become easier to organize and maintain.\par
 Encapsulation protects data inside objects.\par
 Polymorphism allows methods to behave differently in subclasses.\par
\par
Key OOP Terms:\par
1. Class:\par
   A blueprint used to create objects.\par
   Example: Student\par
2. Object:\par
   An instance of a class.\par
   Example: student1 = Student("John", 75)\par
3. Method:\par
   A function inside a class that performs actions.\par
   Example: display_grade()\par
\par
Error Handling:\par
This program handles:\par
1. Missing command-line arguments\par
2. Invalid input (marks that are not numbers)\par
\par
Run Example:\par
python oop_program.py John 85\par
"""\par
\par
import sys\par
\par
\par
# Parent Class\par
class Person:\par
    def __init__(self, name):\par
        self.name = name\par
\par
    def display_info(self):\par
        print(f"Name: \{self.name\}")\par
\par
\par
# Child Class (Inheritance)\par
class Student(Person):\par
    def __init__(self, name, mark):\par
        # Using super() to call parent constructor\par
        super().__init__(name)\par
        self.mark = mark\par
\par
    # Method\par
    def display_grade(self):\par
        print(f"Student: \{self.name\}")\par
        print(f"Mark: \{self.mark\}")\par
\par
        if self.mark >= 50:\par
            print("Result: Pass")\par
        else:\par
            print("Result: Fail")\par
\par
\par
# Main Program\par
try:\par
    # Error Handling: Missing arguments\par
    if len(sys.argv) < 3:\par
        raise IndexError(\par
            "Missing arguments. Please provide a name and a mark."\par
        )\par
\par
    student_name = sys.argv[1]\par
\par
    # Error Handling: Invalid mark input\par
    try:\par
        student_mark = float(sys.argv[2])\par
    except ValueError:\par
        raise ValueError("Invalid input. Mark must be a number.")\par
\par
    # Create object\par
    student1 = Student(student_name, student_mark)\par
\par
    # Call methods\par
    student1.display_info()                                                 \par
    student1.display_grade()\par
\par
except IndexError as e:\par
    print("Error:", e)\par
\par
except ValueError as e:\par
    print("Error:", e)\par
\par
except Exception as e:\par
    print("Unexpected Error:", e)\par

